title: Systematics of fragment angular momentum in low-energy fission of actinides

x4freetext: Systematics of fragment angular momentum in low-energy
fission of actinides

x4codes.hlp: Bhabha Atomic Research Centre (BARC), Trombay, Mumbai, India

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Nuclear Physics, Section A, Vol.587, p.273 (1995)

x4codes.hlp: Bhabha Atomic Research Centre (BARC), Trombay, Mumbai, India

x4freetext: Research Reactors CIRUS and APSARA in
B.A.R.C, Trombay, Mumbai
In the case of neutron-induced fission in reactor
CIRUS, nitrate solutions of 229Th (~ 10 micro gram),
233U (~ 2 micro gram), 235U (~ 2 micro gram),
239pu (~ 2 micro gram), 241pu (~ 2 micro gram) and
245Cm (~ 1 micro gram) were irradiated for 5 s to 30
min at a flux of 5.0x10**12 n/cm2/sec.
In the reactor APSARA, electrodeposited targets
of 229Th (~ 100 micro gram), 241Pu ( ~ 25 micro gram)
and 245Cm ( ~ 4 micro gram) covered with 0.0025 cm
thick aluminium foils were irradiate for 5 min to
60 min at a flux 1.2x10**12 n/cm2/sec.
In case of 252Cf spontaneous fission, recoiling fission
products were collected on 0.0025 cm thick aluminium
foil or ammonium-chloride pellets from an
electrodeposited source (~ 3 micro gram).
The irradiated solutions or aluminium
catcher foils were used for either direct gamma-ray
spectrometry or radiochemical separation of different
fission products such as antimony, tellurium, iodine,
xenon and cesium. The ammonium-chloride pellet
(catcher) in the spontaneous fission of 252Cf was used
for the separation of antimony or xenon.
The aluminium catchers or the standard aliquots
of the separated samples were counted at a fixed
geometry on an 80 cm 3 HPGe detector connected to a 4 K
channel analyser in live-time mode. The resolution of
the detector system was 2.0 keV at 1332.0 keV and the
dead time was always less than 10%.
From the photopeak areas of the gamma rays of the
nuclides` independent isomeric yields were determined
using usual decay-growth equations after correcting for
the precursor contribution.

x4code.headerHelp: Error in value of quantity, defined under ERR-ANALYS

x4freetext: The quoted uncertainty on the independent
isomeric yield ratios include  the errors due to
counting statistics, absolute abundance of the gamma
lines, detector efficiencies, fission yields of the
precursor and the  least square analysis.
The independent isomeric yield ratio for 128Sb, 130Sb,
131Te, 133Te, 134I and 136I in 245Cm(Nth,F) and for
and 154Pm in 249Cf(Nth,F) were deduced from the
literature data of independent/cumulative yields and
using charged-distribution systematics.
